= OpenBazaar =
OpenBazaar supports both TCP and UDP. The latter was added to aid those using it on the clearnet that had difficulties connecting from behind their routers. <ref>https://github.com/OpenBazaar/OpenBazaar/issues/795</ref> When using Tor you don't have to worry about that.

A community demo for OpenBazaar  was done with Tor by hosting seed nodes as Hidden Services <ref>https://www.reddit.com/r/OpenBazaar/comments/2iusp4/openbazaar_tor_demo/</ref>

= Bittorrent Tracker and Client Setup + Onioncat =
This guide is for setting up an alternative and entirely anonymous p2p file sharing set up. Note that it hasn't been tested by Whonix devs yet.

OnionCat Tracker Server Setup : Introduction 

A BitTorrent tracker is a server that assists in the communication between peers using the BitTorrent protocol. OpenTracker is a free BitTorrent peer tracker software that is designed to be fast and to have a low consumption of system resources.

OpenTracker is currently only available from CVS, and as of 2010-12-11, a tarball (*.tar.gz) will be rolled-out soon.
Instructions 

Install CVS and GCC for your Linux operating system prior to installation. In Debian or Ubuntu, this can be done in terminal:

sudo apt-get install cvs build-essential

    Open a terminal (Alt+F2, type 'xterm'), and type

    cvs -d :pserver:cvs@cvs.fefe.de:/cvs -z9 co libowfat

    cd libowfat

    make

    cd ..

    cvs -d:pserver:anoncvs@cvs.erdgeist.org:/home/cvsroot co opentracker

    cd opentracker

    echo "FEATURES+=-DWANT_V6" >> Makefile

    make

    Edit the OpenTracker configuration file, opentracker.conf, such as the sample below. The default settings allow OpenTracker to listen on all interfaces (0.0.0.0:6969/tcp/udp).
    OpenTracker config file

    listen.tcp_udp [fd87:d87e:eb43:5cf4:757c:2be9:5879:d9f7]:6969
    Optional: If you have a webserver running, you can forward GET or HTTP requests
    to your OnionCat IPv6 website; otherwise, comment out.

    tracker.redirect_url http://[fd87:d87e:eb43:5cf4:757c:2be9:5879:d9f7]/

    Run OpenTracker

    ./opentracker.debug -f opentracker.conf

This guide was originally found here <ref>http://anonet2.biz/OnionCat%20BitTorrent%20Tracker.html</ref>.

